You need the concept of JPA `@Inheritance`. Depending on your needs you can choose the inheritance strategy that suits you.

- `InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE` – the entities from different classes with a common ancestor are placed in a single table
- `InheritanceType.JOINED` – each class has its table and querying a subclass entity requires joining the tables
- `InheritanceType.TABLE_PER_CLASS` – all the properties of a class, are in its table, so no join is required

You can write your Entities as:

    @Entity
    @Table(name=&quot;proprieties&quot;)
    @Inheritance(
            strategy = InheritanceType.JOINED
    )
    public class ProprietiesModel {
        @Id
        @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
        private int id;
        private String test;
        private Location location;
        public int getId() {
            return id;
        }
    }

and 

    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;location&quot;)
    public class Location extends ProprietiesModel {
        private String street;
        private int streetNumber;
    }

You can read more in-depth here: 
- https://www.baeldung.com/hibernate-inheritance 
- https://vladmihalcea.com/the-best-way-to-use-entity-inheritance-with-jpa-and-hibernate/

