Sometimes the float **appears** more accurate and sometimes the double **appears** more accurate.  It all depends on the last few bits of the [IEEE754](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754) encoding.

Consider the following:
```java
	  float fa = 3.2f;
	  float fb = 5.7f;

	  double da = 3.2;
	  double db = 5.7;

	  float fr = fa * fb;
	  double dr = da * db;

	  System.out.println(fr);
	  System.out.println(dr);

	  int ifr = Float.floatToRawIntBits(fr);
	  long ldr = Double.doubleToRawLongBits(dr);
	  System.out.println(Integer.toBinaryString(ifr));
	  System.out.println(Long.toBinaryString(ldr));
```
Below I have separated the mantissa from the exponent and aligned them together.

```pre
fr = 18.24
dr = 18.240000000000002
1000001     100100011110101110000101
1000000001  10010001111010111000010100011110101110000101000111110

```
The double version shows a 2 at the end because the finite expansion of the bits don&#39;t end up where it is rounded up or down, getting rid of the trailing 0&#39;s.  The same expansion for the float let&#39;s it be rounded.  This is all dependent on the nature of the numbers in use.  Sometimes it&#39;s the other way around.

And you can actually force situations like this to resolve by manipulating the trailing bits of the mantissa.  But I just use `System.out.printf()` with a format specifier to control my output.

Note:  The rounding I mention is controlled by whatever system you are using beit the `JVM`, `Python`, `C`, etc.  and using hints provided by the cited Wiki link.

